  <h2 id="generalRegistryOffice">Civil Registration and the General Register Office</h2>
   <p> You can find out more about the General Register Office on our [General Register Office page] [link = The General Register Office]. This government office has been responsible for the Civil Registration of births, marriages and deaths in England and Wales since it was formed at the end of 1836 and it became active on 1st July 1837. It creates the indexes that FreeBMD transcribes and, by quoting the information that you found in a record, you can order a certificate from the GRO.</p>
  <p>You can find out more about the data shown against a particular index record on our page: [Understanding the GRO Index Page] [link= "Understanding the GRO Index Page"]; and you can find out more about ordering certificates on our page: [Ordering Certificates] [link= "Ordering Certificates"].</p>
  
  <hr class="rule rule--ornament" />
  <h2 id="districts"> Civil Registration Districts</h2>
  <mark> PC - This section is being worked on - PC </mark>
   <p> In the years prior to government deciding to create a system of National Civil Registration of births, marriages and deaths in England and Wales, the only non-parochial system of large-scale local government was the various Poor Law Unions (the Workhouses), the Unions being created in 1834. Note: County Boroughs and County Councils were not created until 1st April 1889.</p>
  <p> The General Register Office was required to hold a register and an index of the “place” of every event (birth, marriage or death) against a locality and this led to the concept of <em>Registration Districts</em>. Registration Districts were chosen and recommended by the local Guardians of the Workhouses. They were, in effect, groupings of villages and townships located within a larger unit of an individual Poor Law Union. Every Registration District was to have a Registrar and deputy to record the births, marriages and deaths that occurred in their district, in dedicated Registers to be held in a safe place.</p>
   <p>Whilst, the Registration District was often named after the largest village or township in its geographical area, the “area” of the Registration District could be very different from the “area” of the village or township having the same name. Furthermore, a Poor Law Union could cover part of a county, or might cover parts of one than one county.</p>
  <p>As set up, Civil Registration of births, marriages and death involved registered an event against a Registration District, not a county nor a town. However, over the years, the Poor Law Unions were abolished and the Registration Districts were changed in response to population changes; and nowadays, a Registration District is often a local authority, or a sub-section of a large local authority; and confined to a single county.</p>
  <p>You can find out more about the Registration Districts used by the GRO can be found on our page: [District Information] [link = "Districts, Volumes and Pages"]. </p>
  <p>When you find a record of interest, the final part of the Index reference will be in the form: Registration District, Volume No., Page No.. You can find out more about what these values mean on our page: [Understanding the GRO Index Page] [link= "Understanding the GRO Index Page"].</p>  <p>You can also find out more detailed information: including volume and page mappings........</p>
